// @error cannot infer a type for parameter `n`
// An arrow-lambda param with NO contextual type is genuinely uninferable when the lambda is NOT a
// value binding: here it is passed straight to an UN-annotated higher-order parameter (`apply(f)`),
// which gives the emitter nothing to monomorphize against. The compiler reports a clear, actionable
// error asking for an annotation rather than letting an `Unknown` reach codegen. (A lambda bound to
// an un-annotated `const`/`let` is the opposite case — its params are inference holes that
// value-flow-monomorphize per call, exactly like a named generic function — see
// lambda-binding-valueflow.vl.)
function apply(f) f(3)

print(apply((n) => n * 2))
